ent association might be managed. I need to understand if `client_id` is part of the auth header or if it's handled separately to ensure appropriate access control for project data.\n\n\n**Confirming Client Association**\n\nOkay, I've confirmed that `clientAssociation` in the JWT does indeed map to the client account. Examining the mock data and auth details, it's clear the system uses this association to link users to specific client accounts for access control purposes. I've now identified the role-based access based on the association.\n\n\n**Mapping Client Data**\n\nI'm now focusing on mapping the client's data for project access, based on the `clientAssociation` from the JWT. I'm exploring how to translate this `clientAssociation` into the correct `client_id` for project filtering, noting that `clientAssociation` might directly correspond to a `client_name`. I need to handle cases where the `clientAssociation` is a client's `name` and then use that `name` to find the correct `client_id`. I am considering different project filtering options for role access control, and plan to support checking `project.client_name === caller.clientAssociation`.\n\n\n**Defining Project Mock Store**\n\nI'm now deciding where to store the global mutable projects mock store. I'm considering locations like `lib/api-auth.ts`, a new file, or `lib/api-projects.ts`. Currently, I'm leaning toward integrating it with `lib/api-auth.ts`, similar to how `API_MOCK_USERS` is handled, for easy import and consistency within the auth architecture.\n\n\n**Designing Project API Tests**\n\nI'm now going to explore creating an automated test suite. I plan to build a custom test script, like `scripts/test-project-apis.js`, to run tests on the Projects CRUD APIs, similar to `scripts/test-user-apis.js`. This is to ensure all API logic adheres precisely to the specifications. I will start by designing the in-memory global projects store and seeding it with data from `INITIAL_PROJECTS` and `previewProjects`, mapped to corresponding client accounts like `\"client-001\"`.\n\n\n**Populating Mock Project Store**\n\nI'm now populating the mock project store with initial data, mapping client IDs to names. I've defined two initial projects with all required fields, including client associations, status, and health metrics, based on the provided sample data. This is crucial for running the planned API tests.\n\n\n**Expanding Mock Project Data**\n\nI'm now expanding the mock project data store with additional entries, incorporating the remaining sample project data. I'm focusing on ensuring all required fields (`id`, `name`, `client_id`, `client_name`, `phase`, etc.) are correctly represented and that data types align with the API requirements. The new entries will include various `enclaveType` values such as `\"AMD SEV-SNP\"` and `\"AWS Nitro Enclave\"`.\n\n\n**Refining Project Access Controls**\n\nI'm now integrating the access control logic, considering admin versus client roles. Admin roles will have full CRUD access. Clients can list and view projects based on their `client_id`, with restrictions on creating or deleting, unless the role explicitly permits client-admin to create a request-style project. For the MVP, I'm setting up admin create/update/archive and client read-only permissions.\n\n\n**Implementing Admin and Client Roles**\n\nI'm now implementing the admin and client role permissions for the Projects API. The admin role (gff_admin) will have full CRUD access: GET list, GET by ID, POST create, PATCH update, DELETE (or archive). Clients (client_admin, client_member, or those with a client association) will have read-only access (GET list, GET by ID) restricted to projects matching their client association.\n\n\n**Enforcing Client Permissions**\n\nI'm now focusing on enforcing client-specific restrictions for the GET endpoints, ensuring data segregation. I'm verifying that unauthorized client access attempts to view, modify, or delete other client's projects are correctly handled, returning a 403 Forbidden. Client roles will now filter GET requests based on `client_id` with strict enforcement; only projects with the matching `clientAssociation` are accessible. This follows the MVP's client read-only permissions, so the `requestStyle` flag can be implemented later.\n\n\n**Mapping Client ID Lookup**\n\nI'm now mapping the `clientAssociation` string from the JWT to its respective `client_id`, for more accurate filtering. I am looking at examples like `\"Apex Sovereign Group [Preview Client]\"` and its corresponding `client_id` `\"client-001\"`. I've created the helper function to perform these lookups. This should prevent authentication errors with clients.\n\n\n**Verifying Auth Caller Returns**\n\nI'm now verifying the `getAuthCaller` return structure, confirming it returns `{ caller: user }` containing `clientAssociation` and `role`. The `getClientIdFromAssociation` function I defined works well. I'm clarifying role-based filtering: admins can access all data, and clients are filtered by `client_id` determined from `clientAssociation`, ensuring only projects with matching `client_id` or `client_name` are accessible.\n\n\n**Defining API Internal Design**\n\nI'm now outlining the API internal design plan, focusing on back-end aspects instead of frontend elements. This involves detailing how I handle filter parameters. Specifically, for the `client_id` filter, I'll enforce strict client-specific filtering, preventing unauthorized access. I'll outline handling of `phase`, `status`, `health`, `owner`, and `search` parameters, and map them to their corresponding use cases. The plan will encompass handling filter parameters and internal control points.\n\n\n**Designing API Endpoints**\n\nNow I'm designing the projects API endpoints `/api/v1/projects` and `/api/v1/projects/[id]`. These routes will be secure, RESTful, JSON-based, and follow standard API conventions. I plan to define the request-response cycle and schema, using a metaphor of secure gateway tunnels and cryptographic ledgers. I plan to incorporate clean request-response cycles, precise error logging, and standard CORS/Bearer authentication.\n\n\n**Refining Projects API Endpoints**\n\nI'm working on refining the projects API endpoints, focusing on implementation details. I've defined `API_MOCK_PROJECTS` in `lib/api-projects.ts` for in-memory global state, with related interface definitions, seeding logic, and helper functions. I am implementing the routes: `/app/api/v1/projects/route.ts` for listing (GET) and creating (POST), and `/app/api/v1/projects/[id]/route.ts` for fetching (GET by ID), updating (PATCH), and deleting (DELETE). Plus I'll write `scripts/test-project-apis.js` for automation. I've also noted files to avoid. I am clarifying the required interface, and plan to include the filters required.\n\n\n**Integrating Project Data**\n\nI'm now integrating the `ApiProject` interface and initial mock data within `lib/api-auth.ts`. I've precisely reviewed lines 145-185, adding the interface, the default mock project data, global database initialization, and generator functions after the user-specific functions. I've begun drafting project seed data, including fields like status, health, owner, and enclave type to align with the API requirements.\n\n\n**Populating Mock Project Data**\n\nI'm now populating the projects' mock data store with sample project entries, carefully adding the project data from the instructions. I'm focusing on ensuring all the fields, including those from the existing mock entries, are correctly represented and match the API requirements.\n\n\n**Adding Mock Project Data**\n\nI'm now incorporating additional mock project entries to diversify the test data. I'm adding a project from \"Sovereign Logistics Unit\" and \"Federal Treasury Multi-Enclave Ledger\" to ensure the `client_id` and `client_name` mapping are handled correctly. I will continue to add entries to test all API functionalities, including the